{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:36:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:36:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.55,0.02,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107499"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1805"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39420"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107499"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a four week history of scrotal swelling. He first noticed the swelling after a game of soccer, when he thought he might have been injured in that area after a rough tackle. The left side of the scrotum and contents are normal and on the right side there is a firm 6 cm diameter non-tender swelling which does not transilluminate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound confirms a homogenous intratesticular mass of low echogenicity compared to the normal testicular tissue. The patient has a CT of the chest-abdomen-pelvis which shows no evidence of lymph node involvement or distant metastases. There is no elevation of alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) or human chorionic gonadotropin (HCG).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active surveillance","Radical orchiectomy","Chemotherapy","Retroperitoneal lymph node dissection","Radiation therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most important diagnosis to consider is testicular cancer. Initial assessment involves scrotal ultrasound, followed by CT imaging with contrast of the chest-abdomen-pelvis to allow for tumour staging. In this case the tumour is confined to the testicle, there are normal levels of serum tumour markers and the CT scan is normal. It is most probable that this patient has a stage 1 seminoma. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadical orchiectomy\u003C/strong\u003E alone will cure most patients with stage 1 seminoma and can confirm the diagnosis on histology. Thus, this answer is the most correct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive surveillance \u003C/strong\u003Eis appropriate for patients who have been treated with orchiectomy as 10-20% of patients experience disease relapse. This patient has not yet had an orchiectomy so this answer is incorrect because the patient still needs definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis available as an adjuvant therapy to orchiectomy for patients who are not able to undergo active surveillance or desire reduced risk of relapse but is not an appropriate definitive treatment and is therefore incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal lymph node dissection \u003C/strong\u003Emay be appropriate for a stage 1 non-seminoma to reduce the risk of relapse but this has not yet been diagnosed, thus this answer is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation therapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis an appropriate alternative to chemotherapy but again is not an appropriate definitive treatment and is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scrotal swellings will often go unnoticed until some apparent trauma brings the problems to the patient\u0027s attention."],"references":["Chovanec M, Cheng L. Advances in diagnosis and treatment of testicular cancer. BMJ. 2022;379:e070499. doi: 10.1136/bmj-2022-070499. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/379/bmj-2022-070499"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89979"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T14:48:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T14:51:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1805"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107499"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attrib